<comment type="disruption phenotype">
<text evidence="10 11 17">Lethality. In the presence of 1% protein cells grow extremely slowly and are blocked at the predivisional two-cell stage of the cell cycle. In the absence of Era and Rnc there is an additional defect in chromosome partitioning. In depletion experiments cells grow normally for 2 hours when protein levels fall. After 4 hours 16S rRNA levels decrease with a concomitant rise in the 17S precursor rRNA molecule (extra sequences at both the 5' and 3' end compared to mature 16S rRNA) and a loss of 70S ribosome assembly.</text>
</comment>
<comment type="miscellaneous">
<text evidence="3 6 16">When overexpressed partially suppresses the slow growth and decreased 70S ribosome phenotype of an rsgA knockout; RsgA may be involved in 30S ribosomal subunit biogenesis (PubMed:18223068). When overexpressed partially suppresses the 30S ribosomal subunit assembly defects and cold-sensitivity of an rbfA knockout; an era mutant missing residues 39-49 fully suppresses these phenotypes (PubMed:12753192). Overexpression is not able to suppress a rimM disruption phenotype nor a C23U mutation in 16S rRNA. Also suppresses temperature-sensitive mutations in DNA primase (PubMed:9093842).</text>
</comment>
<comment type="similarity">
<text evidence="18">Belongs to the TRAFAC class TrmE-Era-EngA-EngB-Septin-like GTPase superfamily. Era GTPase family.</text>
</comment>
